<br>
The topic of the post &quot;Hasted delays ARE fractional&quot; means that the delay of a weapon when recalculated to compensate for haste is not rounded up or down to the next number.  <br>
<br>
ie --- if you got a hasted delay of 16.25 it would not be rounded to a flat 16<br>
<br>
The math equations and pages upon pages of information are put up here to defend that premise.<br>
<br>
HOWEVER, the testers are missing one of the simplest solutions to get around the dual strike issue.  Taking the information and parsing it as packets of information within X timeframe as a single/dual strike is unreliable due to any of the forms of lag.  Seeing as how dual strikes are random  it would throw a random variable into the equation that would give you an inaccurate number of swings overall thus invalidating your research.  The easiest way around it is parse the information of a bard or beastlord near the same level as the tester.  This will give you the same general skill caps as they relate to the weapons used by the Vah Shir as well as giving you two single hand weapons to get the distinct dmg types to aid in parsing and you don't have to worry about the inaccuracies of a dual strike that popped into your log file as 2 seperate swings due to a split second of lag.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ugnix.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gnix</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/24/02 4:53:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousethebackroomsecretsspoilers.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11593.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hasted delays ARE fractional</span><hr size=1> An easy way to measure the server heartbeat would be to group with a bard and count the number of times you get the song message.  That should be the number of &quot;ticks&quot; that occur during your test. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uparticleboy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>particleboy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/25/02 1:26:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousethebackroomsecretsspoilers.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11593.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hasted delays ARE fractional</span><hr size=1> Whoa Gnix, nice idea.  Time to get me a bard. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ugraalthedorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Graal the Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/25/02 1:46:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousethebackroomsecretsspoilers.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11593.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hasted delays ARE fractional</span><hr size=1> Even better would be to test using the bard. Bards don't have double attack, so you don't have that random element screwing up results.<br>
<br>
